body:
Having connectors inside connectors can sometimes not work as expected.

Let's take an example that produce such an infinite loop: 

```js
const CustomHits = connectHits(props => {
  // infinite loop
  const hits = props.hits.map(hit => {
    const rl = <RefinementList 
                            attributeName="materials"
                            transformItems={items => items}
               />;
    return <div>{hit.name} {rl}</div>;
  });
  return <div>{hits}</div>;
});
```

When the `hits` renders, the `componentWillReceiveProps` of the `refinementList` is called. Because the reference of the `transformItems`change each time, then it calls a new search, and we end up in an infinite loop.

This is fixable on the user side by doing this:

```js
const transformItems = (items) => items;
const CustomHits = connectHits(props => {
  // infinite loop
  const hits = props.hits.map(hit => {
    const rl = <RefinementList 
                            attributeName="materials"
                            transformItems={transformItems}
               />;
    return <div>{hit.name} {rl}</div>;
  });
  return <div>{hits}</div>;
});
```

However this might not be intuitive for everybody. We probably need to add something about it in a guide on the documentation website.  Also to avoid any issue of this type, we can do a deepEqual when checking if a component should update instead of a shallow equal, but it will results to something less efficient. 

Nesting connectors means that they do not register at the same time, which is causing two searches to be triggered. I believe that's why including the <Stats/> inside the <SearchBox/> on a very big index, also triggered an infinite loop (the stats numbers changed between the two searches).
